<p><b>Consumerism</b> is the equation of personal <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a> with <a href="/wiki/Consumption_(economics)" title="Consumption (economics)">consumption</a> and the purchase of material possessions.<br /></p>
<p>The term is often associated with criticisms of consumption starting with <a href="/wiki/Thorstein_Veblen" title="Thorstein Veblen">Thorstein Veblen</a>.</p>
<p>Veblen's subject of examination, the newly emergent middle class arising at the turn of the twentieth century, comes to full fruition by the end of the twentieth century through the process of <a href="/wiki/Globalization" title="Globalization">globalization</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>, consumerism refers to economic policies placing emphasis on consumption. In an abstract sense, it is the belief that the free choice of consumers should dictate the economic structure of a society (cf. <a href="/wiki/Producerism" title="Producerism">Producerism</a>, especially in the British sense of the term).<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since January 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
